prompt.user:
Project: {project_name} Client: {client_name} Methodology: {methodology} Service Lines: {service_lines}
Project Type Guidance: {project_type_guidance}
SOW Summary: {sow_summary}
Service Line Design Standards: {standards_context}
Platform Combination Patterns (proven integration patterns for this service line mix): {combinations_context}
Generated Requirements Context (if available): {requirements_context}
FORMAT GUIDE ONLY — READ CAREFULLY BEFORE GENERATING: The example below is for a COMPLETELY DIFFERENT fictional project (Meridian Insurance). DO NOT copy any of the following from the example into your output: - Role names (Claims Agent, Claims Supervisor, IT Service Desk) — derive role names from THIS project's SOW and requirements above - Numbers (12,000 agents, 200 IT staff, 90 days) — use numbers only if they appear in THIS project's context - Named credentials or policy names (MFA-SF-Agents, MuleSoft_SF_Integration) — name these based on THIS project - Specific table names unless they match THIS project's service lines The example shows ONLY the structure and depth of each table. All content must come from the actual project context above.
FORMAT EXAMPLE (fictional project — structure only):
### Authentication and Authorization Model | Layer | Auth Mechanism | Authorization Model | Notes | |-------|---------------|--------------------|----| | [Service Line] (human users) | [SSO mechanism native to this service line] | [Permission model native to this service line — SF uses Permission Sets, SN uses Roles, Azure uses RBAC] | [User count if known from SOW, MFA policy] | | [Service Line] (API / integration) | [Machine auth mechanism] | [Scope restriction] | [Where secret is stored] |
### Role Definitions | Role | Description | Access Scope | Service Line | |------|-------------|--------------|--------------| | [Role from SOW user types] | [What this user does in the project] | [Specific objects they can access in the platform] | [Which service line] |
END OF FORMAT EXAMPLE.
Now generate the security architecture document for {project_name} — client {client_name}, service lines: {service_lines}. Role names must come from the actual user types mentioned in the SOW and requirements above — not from the example. Auth mechanisms must match the actual service lines: Salesforce uses Permission Sets, ServiceNow uses Roles, Azure uses Managed Identities. OWASP mitigations must name the actual framework being used in this project. Do not copy any names, numbers, or details from the format example. Output ONLY markdown.
